anuary 1267":"before 20 January 1267","Abt 1249":"about 1249","1253":"1253","1252":"1252","1251":"1251","Abt 1219":"about 1219","1281":"1281","1305":"1305","1502":"1502","1249":"1249","1259":"1259","1224":"1224","1267":"1267","1222":"1222","1219":"1219","Scales Hall, Middleton, Norfolk, England":"Middleton, Norfolk, England","Middleton, Norfolk, England":"Middleton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Hertfordshire, England":"Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Scales","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","plural form of   Scale  , naming a herdsman living and working on a summer pasture, or a habitational name for someone from a place called Scales, mostly minor places in Lancashire and Yorkshire.   Scholes   is a dialect variant of the same name.","(of Norman origin): habitational name either from Écalles-Alix (Seine-Maritime), Écalles (in Estouteville-Écalles, Seine-Maritime), or from Escalles (Pas-de-Calais). The earliest spellings of these names suggest a derivation from Latin <i>scala</i>, <i>scalae</i> (plural) ‘ladder, staircase, stile’, perhaps applied to a steep slope or path, although Old Norse <i>skáli</i> (‘herdsman's hut, shieling’, see   Scale  ) has also been suggested for Écalles.   Challis   may be a variant of the same name. The surname has also been established in southern Ireland (Limerick) since the 14th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Scholes","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or other of the places called Scholes in Lancashire and Yorkshire, or from Scole in Norfolk, all named with Middle English <i>scole</i> or <i>scoles</i> ‘herdsman's hut(s)’ (Old Norse <i>skáli</i>). In northern England the name was sometimes interchangeable with   Scales  , a dialect variant of the same word."]},{"name":"Scale","meanings":["English: from northern Middle English <i>scale</i> ‘herdsman's hut, shed, shieling’ (Old Norse <i>skáli</i>). The surname may have denoted a herdsman who lived and worked on a summer pasture or someone from any of several mostly minor places so named in Lancashire and Yorkshire. The name often varies between singular and plural forms; see   Scales  ."]},{"name":"Schooley","meanings":["English (Sussex): variant of <b>Scholey</b>, a habitational name either from Scholey's Bridge in Hemsworth (Yorkshire) or the lost Scholey in Rastrick (Yorkshire), recorded in that spelling in 1399. The placenames derive from Old Norse <i>skáli</i> ‘(temporary) hut, shed, shieling’ + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare   Scales  ."]},{"name":"Schoolcraft","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Scowcroft</b>, from Middle English <i>scale</i>, <i>sc(h)ole</i> ‘hut, shed’ (Old Norse <i>skáli</i>) + <i>croft</i> ‘small enclosed field’. The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in or by a field containing a hut, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Scowcroft in Oldham (Lancashire) and Scholecroft in Morley (Yorkshire). Compare   Scales   and   Schofield  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":5,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":40,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Scales II was born about 1219, in Hertfordshire, England as the son of Robert Scales Ii and ?. He died before 20 January 1267, in Middleton, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1219–Bef 20 January 1267":"umbes 1219–enne 20. jaanuari 1267","1219–1267":"1219–1267","1222–1267":"1222–1267","1249–1305":"1249–1305","1251–Male":"1251–Surnud","1253–1281":"1253–1281","1252–Male":"1252–Surnud","1502–Male":"1502–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","Bef 20 January 1267":"enne 20. jaanuari 1267","Abt 1249":"umbes 1249","1253":"1253","1252":"1252","1251":"1251","Abt 1219":"